-- Apex, Bayan, Daewoo, Inotera, Nanya, Qantas: Asia Ex-Japan Stock Preview
-- Ian C. Sayson
-- 2010-07-21T18:38:03Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-21/apex-bayan-daewoo-inotera-nanya-qantas-asia-ex-japan-stock-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes in  Asian trading , excluding Japan. Stock
symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  
 Aditya Birla Minerals Ltd.  (ABY AU): The unit of India’s
second-largest copper producer, Hindalco Industries Ltd., said
production at its mines in Australia rose 35 percent to 17,292
metric tons in the quarter ended June 30. The Perth-based
company said is considering restarting its Mount Gordon mines.
The stock gained 0.7 percent to 71.5 Australian cents.  
 Apex Mining Co.  (APX PM): The Philippine gold producer said
a hole drilled in its Maco mine “intersected high grade gold”
in a previously untested part of the project. Apex A shares,
which are reserved for Filipinos, increased 3.9 percent to 2.70
pesos on July 19.  Its B shares  (APXB PM), which have no
ownership restrictions, decreased 3.9 percent to 2.90 pesos on
July 19.  
 Daewoo Shipbuilding & Marine Engineering Co.  (042660 KS):
The world’s second-largest shipbuilder said it received a $975
million order for 10 container vessels, its first box-ship
contract in two years, as the global economic rebound revives
world trade. The stock rose 1.6 percent to 19,700 won.  
 Hyundai Heavy Industries Co.  (009540 KS): Second-quarter
profit at the world’s largest shipyard more than doubled to a
better-than-expected 910.5 billion won ($756 million) after
building more offshore structures and paying less for raw
materials. The company was expected to make a 708 billion won
profit based on the average of 21  analyst estimates  compiled by
Bloomberg. The stock rose 3.9 percent to 256,500 won.  
 Inotera Memories Inc.  (3474 TT): Taiwan’s third-largest
memory-chip maker posted a second-quarter net loss of NT$1.8
billion ($56 million) on sales of NT$11.3 billion. The stock
decreased 0.6 percent to NT$18.2.  
 Korea Electric Power Corp.  (015760 KS): South Korea’s
largest utility will buy a 20 percent stake in  PT Bayan
Resources  (BYAN IJ) for about $515 million to add supplies of
coal used to generate half the electricity in Asia’s fourth-
biggest economy. The Seoul-based utility will purchase 667
million shares of the Indonesian coal producer for 7,000 rupiah
each, Korea Electric said in a regulatory filing. Korea Electric
fell 0.6 percent to 31,900 won. Bayan rose 0.7 percent to 7,250
rupiah.  
 Nanya Technology Co.  (2408 TT): Taiwan’s second-largest
chipmaker posted a second-quarter loss of NT$1 billion on sales
of NT$15.7 billion, the company said. The stock gained 0.6
percent to NT$24.8  
 Qantas Airways Ltd.  (QAN AU): Australia’s biggest airline
will buy seven new Q400 NextGen aircraft from Bombardier
Aerospace valued at approximately $218 million based on the list
price, the carrier said in an e-mailed statement. The stock
climbed 0.8 percent to A$2.40.  
 Samsung Electronics Co.  (005930 KS): Infineon Technologies
AG is considering formation of a cell-phone chip venture with
its South Korean competitor Samsung, Manager-Magazin reported on
its website, without saying where it obtained the information.
Samsung, Asia’s biggest maker of chips, climbed 2.4 percent to
817,000 won.  
 Telstra Corp.  (TLS AU): Australia’s largest telephone
company will cut about 10 percent of its executive jobs to
simplify its business. The changes will involve about 30
executives losing their positions while a further 300 senior
management roles will be eliminated, spokeswoman Julia Foley
said in an e-mailed statement. The stock decreased 0.6 percent
to A$3.22.  
